		<profileDesc>
			<abstract>
				<p>We consider the problem of learning accurate models from multiple sources of &quot;nearby&quot; data. Given distinct samples from multiple data sources and estimates of the dissimilarities between these sources, we provide a general theory of which samples should be used to learn models for each source. This theory is applicable in a broad decision-theoretic learning framework, and yields results for classification and regression generally, and for density estimation within the exponential family. A key component of our approach is the development of approximate triangle inequalities for expected loss, which may be of independent interest.</p>
			</abstract>
